         <abstract>
            <p> The Gize ṣalot  is a version of the <title ref="LIT1961Mashaf">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</title>, a Church service made up of psalms, biblical readings and hymns. 
               However, it is actually a genre of its own, a Gize ṣalot for the use of hermits and recluses.
               <bibl><ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/> <citedRange unit="page">270</citedRange></bibl> follow the Ethiopian distribution of the psalter.</p>
           <p>The three other types of Maṣḥafa saʿātāt identified by  <bibl><ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy "/>
               <citedRange unit="page">266</citedRange></bibl> are: </p>
               <p> the <title ref="LIT2230Saatat"/>, which comes from the Copto-Arabic tradition;</p>
            <p> the <title ref="LIT3575Mashaf">Saʿātāt of <persName ref="PRS4709Giyorgis">Giyorgis of Saglā</persName></title>, 
               which replaced the Saʿātāt za-gǝbṣ and is presently in use in Ethiopia and Eritrea;</p>
            <p> a <title ref="LIT3576Saatat">Saʿātāt that includes the entire Psalter</title> in the daily pensum </p>
           <p><listBibl type="secondary"><bibl><ptr target="bm:ZanettiFritsch2014Saatat"/></bibl></listBibl></p>
